  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity worldwide. It is considered a serious financial crime and is criminalized under the laws of most countries, including China. Money laundering involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. The goal is to make the proceeds appear as though they come from a legitimate source.\n\nIn China, the legal framework for combating money laundering is robust and includes the Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China, which was enacted in 2007. This law establishes the regulatory requirements for financial institutions and outlines the measures for preventing and combating money laundering activities. China also collaborates with international organizations and other countries to strengthen the global fight against money laundering and the financing of terrorism.\n\nAuthorities in China take a firm stance against money laundering, and individuals or entities found guilty of engaging in such activities can face severe penalties, including substantial fines and imprisonment. The Chinese government is committed to maintaining the integrity of its financial system and adheres strictly to international standards in the fight against money laundering.",
